post_text:
We are planning to have a Fall Musical this year, and it will be "The 25th Annual Putnam County Spelling Bee."
The smaller cast and the natural spacing on stage allows the show to be a good fit during these times.
Because of the smaller cast, auditions will unfortunately be limited to students in grades 10-12. Students who are interested in participating should fill out a form outside the media center and give it to Mr Cheney.
Shows are scheduled for Nov 20-22.

post_text:
The MSHSL today voted to move football and volleyball to the spring. Tennis, swimming and cross country are still in the fall.

There will be four sports seasons this year: non-postponed fall sports in the fall, winter sports, postponed fall sports in the spring, and spring sports in the summer (until early July).

Football and volleyball will be allowed to hold practices in the fall. Spring sports can practice in the fall as well.

Stay tuned for more details...

post_text:
It's been a long and interesting journey - but there WILL BE performances of "Grease."

To comply with state COVID guidelines, we've had to reduce the size of the cast, remove some choreography, and place the singers upstage. BUT - you'll still hear the story and enjoy all those classic songs performed by some very talented young people!

Again, to comply with guidelines, only 75 tickets per show will be available. They are available from cast members, directors and at the school office. You MUST have a ticket to enter the building. We've decided to make the tickets free, but would appreciate Drama Club donations at the door.

A summer volleyball camp is being planned for high school players from July 20-24.

Join Head Volleyball Coach Jacob Voss and his staff for your summer volleyball training. All volleyball camps include training on fundamental skills (passing, setting, attacking, serving, defense, & blocking). We will also train offensive and defensive strategies with two-on-two, three-on-three and six-on-six game competitions.

GRADES 9-12
8:00AM-11:00AM
FEE: $40 (Shirt included)

Mark your calendars. Registration will begin soon.

Upsala's drive-in graduation will be this Saturday in the school parking lot. The event will start at 1:30 pm.

Only one vehicle per graduating senior will be allowed in the parking lot. Others will need to watch or listen from off school property.

The event will be live streamed on Facebook with a camera on the stage, and there will also be a Zoom feed.

If you watch from home, please watch the Facebook feed. The Zoom feed will have a limited number of people who can watch.

Specific links will be available the day of the event.

post_text:
The Upsala School District and community are saddened to learn of the passing of Connor Throener, a 17-year-old Junior at Swanville High School. Connor was unable to recover from his injuries suffered in a tragic car accident. It is even more difficult for everyone during this pandemic, as people are not as able to get together in large groups to grieve. Connor will live on in many lives and continue to touch people with his generous spirit, as Connor had made the decision to be an organ donor. Our deepest sympathies go out to Connor’s family at this time. Keep them in your thoughts and prayers. We have listed some resources for parents and students to reach out to as we all struggle through this difficult time.

Chaplain Gregg Valentine from Morrison County:
morchaplain@gmail.com, 320-630-7876

Kari Prokott, School Social Worker

Also, you can use these as resources
Crisis Text Line: Text MN to 741741 or Crisis Phone line: 1-800-462-5525

post_text:
If your child is experiencing any mental health symptoms

-depressive symptoms (sadness, losing interest in previously enjoyed activities, difficulty focusing)
-anxiety (excessive worry, racing thoughts, trouble concentrating)
-change in sleeping/eating patterns
-change in attitude
-excessive fear/guilt
-extreme mood shifts

Please make a referral to Northern Pines at https://www.npmh.org/ and click “Child Online Referral” on the upper right of the screen. Northern Pines is taking referrals and can deliver services via telehealth to your computer or smart phone.

post_text:
Following the governor's press conference today, here is the current plan for school (unless something changes):
Distance learning will occur from March 30-April 30, with students coming back to the school building on May 5. We will also work to reschedule major spring activities such as prom and the musical. We do not yet know what a spring sports schedule might look like.
Look for another official statement from Superintendent Capelle soon.

post_text:
In planning for distance learning we would like to offer a curbside pick up of Learning Resources on Thursday and Friday. Some electronic devices will be ready for distribution on Friday.
We would like you to drive up to the main doors (“A") between 1pm - 4pm, stay in your car for assistance and then we will bring out anything we have for your family.
If you are unable to come and do curbside pickup, then the plan is to have items delivered to your home sometime next week.

post_text: ON TO STATE!
shared_text:
Royalton Public Schools
February 15 at 10:16 PM ·

Congrats to our 2020 Section 7A Wrestling Champions!!

They will compete as a team in the Class A State Wrestling Tournament held at Xcel Energy Center on February 27. The Royals defeated Crosby-Ironton, Holdingford, and Aitkin to claim their first section title since 2009 and second in program history. Congrats to Coach Gorecki and his staff and all of our wrestlers! A big thank you to our Royalton-Upsala parents for helping us host the 7A Team Sections this year. Go Royals!

post_text:
**UPDATE ON JACE**

It had been planned on Thursday that Jace was going to come to the school and share his amazing smile and energy.

Unfortunately, he won't be coming to see us all again as he has been flown to the hospital.

His mom and sister will (hopefully) be gracing us with their presence on Thursday, December 19th around 2:35pm and will accept all that you, your children, the staff and community have generously given. If they cannot make it, we will hand deliver the donations.

Please make any checks out to the Josephson Family.

post_text: The preschoolers have completed their service learning project “Cookies for the Community.” They collected change, went to the bank to watch the change machine and were excited to get $114 to make cookies. They helped mix up the ingredients and teachers baked them. Each preschooler signed up for a local business to deliver cookies with their family and say “Thanks” by GIVING to our community members who are so supportive of our school.
